in recent decades, and the challenge has become more intense since the 1990s. The decline of communism and socialism as ideologies, and the decreasing importance of national boundaries for capital, companies and even labour, have had profound implications for national identity. Thus, the impact of globalization on "nation-states" is not identical. How have "nation-states" coped with globalization? Has it led to stronger nationalism or national disintegration? What has happened to national identity? Is the concept of "nation" still relevant in the era of globalization? To answer these questions, twelve countries -- six from the West (France, UK, USA, Yugoslavia, Australia, and Russia) and six from Asia (Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Japan, China, and India) have been selected for study. These countries represent a wide range of national experiences — from "old" states to "new" states, from mono-ethnic nations to multi-ethnic ones, and from surviving nation-states to decaying ones. Apart from the individual country studies, the last chapter summarizes and compares the findings of these country studies, throwing light on the various types of nationalism, and the gains and losses of these countries in the process of globalization  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGlobalizationxCongresses. 0aGlobalization--Congresses. 0aNationalismxCongresses. 0aNationalism--Congresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh1 aCibulka, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilberg, Trond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodson, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInoguchi, Takashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David Martin, econtribut